
jQuery is a client side library that works across multiple browsers. 



:: .val() ::

Getting the current value of the first element in the set of matched elements
*Does not accept arguments
Used primarily to get the values of form elements such as: 
  input, select and textarea

:: .val( value ) ::

Sets the value of each element in a set of matched elements

Value types: String, Number, Array

  :: .val(function) ::

  Function returning the value to set. this is the current element. Receives the index position of the element in the set and the old value as arguments.

Typically used to set te values of form fields

|| [] = if (mv.length == 0){ mv = []}


:: .attr vs .prop ::
.prop() provides a way to explicitly retrieve property values
.attr() retrieves attributes

:: .attr(attributeName) ::
Type: String
Get the value of an attribute value for only the first element in the matched set. 

:: .attr(attributeName, value) :: 
AttributeName = String
value = Number/String

:: .attr(attrbutes) ::
PlainObject - an object of attribute-value pairs to set

:: .attr(attributeName, function) ::
$( "#id" ).attr("title", function( i, val ){
  return val + "- photo by kelly clark"
});

http://jquery-howto.blogspot.com/2011/06/html-difference-between-attribute-and.html

http://jsbin.com/lizavojuwa/1/edit

:: .prop() ::
Sets or returns properties and values of the selected elements.
It should be used with:
  selectedIndex - returns an integer
  tagName - returns tag name of the element
  nodeName
  nodeType
  ownerDocument
  defaultChecked
  defaultSelected